            "id": "electron-configuration-orbitals",
            "title": "Electron Configuration and Orbitals",
            "text": "**Electron configuration** describes how electrons are distributed among energy levels and orbitals. The **Aufbau principle** states that electrons fill orbitals from lowest to highest energy. **Hund's rule** states that electrons fill degenerate orbitals with parallel spins before pairing.\n\n**Orbitals** are regions of space where electrons are most likely to be found. The four main orbital types are **s** (spherical), **p** (dumbbell-shaped), **d** (complex shapes), and **f** (very complex). Each orbital can hold a maximum of 2 electrons with opposite spins.\n\n**Energy levels** are numbered 1, 2, 3... with sublevels s, p, d, f. The maximum number of electrons in each level follows 2n², where n is the level number. For example, level 2 can hold 2(2)² = 8 electrons.\n\nUnderstanding electron configuration explains why **neon lights glow different colors**—each noble gas has a unique electron arrangement that produces characteristic light when excited. This principle is used in advertising signs and decorative lighting.",
