            "id": "periodic-trends",
            "title": "Periodic Trends",
            "text": "**Periodic trends** are patterns in element properties that repeat across periods and groups. **Atomic size** generally decreases across a period (left to right) due to increasing nuclear charge pulling electrons closer, and increases down a group due to additional energy levels.\n\n**Ionization energy** (energy to remove an electron) increases across periods due to stronger nuclear attraction, and decreases down groups due to electrons being farther from nucleus. **Electronegativity** (ability to attract electrons) follows similar patterns.\n\nThese trends help predict element behavior and properties. In Ghana, understanding periodic trends is crucial for **selecting appropriate metals for construction in coastal areas**. Metals with low ionization energy and high reactivity (like iron) corrode faster in salty coastal air, while more noble metals (like aluminum) resist corrosion better.",
